The paper deals with the problem of reaching consensus in a network with Byzantine faults, which is a topic in distributed computing (cs.DC). The use of multi-hop communication and network connectivity are also important aspects of the paper, which could place it in the sub-categories of networked systems (cs.NI) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also involves investigating the impact of network topology on the algorithm's correctness, which could place it in the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT) or control and systems theory (cs.SY).
